 Preamble

 The licenses for most software are designed to take away your
 freedom to share and change it.  By contrast, the GNU Lesser General
 Public License is designed to allow developers and companies to use
 and integrate software released under the LGPL into their own (even
 proprietary) software without being required to release the source
 code of their own components.  The LGPL allows them to do this by
 requiring that modifications to the LGPL-covered components themselves
 be released under the same license, while allowing proprietary
 components to remain closed-source.

 This version of the LGPL applies to certain designated software
 packages, and to any other software for which the copyright holders
 have choose to use it.  The terms are similar to those of the GNU
 General Public License (GPL), but not as restrictive on combined works.

